See you then, bye for now!!

commText: B0$ That has been my motto, always taken calls on situations. T20 is very funny, a couple of sixes can change your mind. Captaincy is something I back my instincts on. Me and Ashu Pa have a similar mindset, we back our calls and we have similar calls. Today, the idea of bowling Rashid and Noor was simple. They like pace with Green and Tim David who are big hitters, and that's why we wanted to offer them spin and offer them spinners that are difficult to read. Wanted to close the game early because a couple of games haven't gone in our favour recently. (On Abhinav Manohar) I think it is all hardwork, he bats 2 hours in the nets everyday it feels like, he's been our best death overs hitter. We spoke to him last year and there were a few things he had to improve on, and this year he's come out blazing.

B0$ It's good so far, few things I am working on to be more consistent with line and length. Happy that I got some wickets but at the same time, need to work on a few areas. Looking forward to the rest of the season as well. Those first 3 overs, managed to keep them quiet. As long as you're hitting the right areas, I feel it's pretty hard for the batters to go after. That was in my mind. (On Noor Ahmad) It's great to have him in the side and sharing the bowling partnership with him since last year. That kid, he just wants to learn and he's working so hard. Last year the way he was working, bowling lots in the nets, kept asking the questions. Even when I was in the gym, he was coming to the gym and saying, 'let's bowl here in the gym.' At 1AM, 2 AM he was bowling with me in the gym. He wanted to get better and perform. He got the opportunity now and he's been delivering. I am so happy for him that he's delivering. It's a great news for GT and also for Afghanistan.

B0$ That's a little disappointing, we had control of the game and the last few overs went for a few too many runs. Every team has different strengths, we have a good batting line up and we back ourselves to go out and get that target, today wasn't our today. There was some dew and we needed someone to bat a little deeper. We came pretty close in the last game while chasing 215 but we didn't start well with the bat today and that is not the right thing when chasing 200+. Even in the last 7 overs we didn't have many batters batting in the middle.

B0$ What a mismatch!! Who will say that MI are five-time champions off the back of that performance? Ishan Kishan struggles to rotate strike, Rohit hasn’t found consistency and their death bowling would be giving all their fans nightmares. Oh how badly do they miss Bumrah…. But at the other end of the spectrum, we saw the reigning champions remind us all why they hold the crown. Shubman Gill got another fifty, and today their middle-order joined the party with Abhinav Manohar and David Miller getting vital cameos. They even got their iceman Rahul Tewatia to come out and smoke a few sixes at the death as the hosts registered their highest score in the IPL. In reply, once again Shami and Pandya made it look like GT were offered a different pitch to bowl on with the amount of swing they were able to generate. Rohit fell cheaply, and MI just couldn't break loose in the powerplay. Then came Rashid Khan and Noor Ahmad, as the two Afghan spinners caused the opposition so many problems in the middle-overs. Rashid picked two, and Noor Ahmed claimed three wickets to bury the game. SKY threatened for a bit, but couldn't bat long enough. Then Nehal Wadhera and Piyush Chawla struck a few lusty blows to reduce the margin of defeat. But still, a crushing defeat for MI. Over to the presentations now...

commText: B0$ IPL is a tournament where you need to be on your toes even if you are not playing, you have to be ready. Thankfully whenever I have been called upon by any of my franchises, I have been able to deliver. I take a lot of pride in that. Lots of hard work goes behind the scenes as well. I believe in my processes. There might be situations where you need to try something else, but trying to get wickets or dot balls through your stock balls, just being smart enough with your lengths is enough. (On LSG game) It was a wicket where I thought it will spin more, but as the ball got older it started to grip. So my role in the powerplay and in the last two overs were quite different. Happy to be at the right side of that game.

B0$ We had the belief in the bowling unit that we can defend the total (against LSG). The mindset was to take it as close as possible. We focused on our basics and we won the game. My economy is slightly on the higher side compared to my last 5-6 seasons, I have bowled a few loose deliveries and the batsmen are punishing them. I am trying to reduce the number loose balls, trying to bowl in the right channel. Amazing feeling (playing in Ahmedabad), there were more 100,000 people for the first game. Even for the day match, there were around 80,000 people. This is what the home is all about - the love and support we get, I am so lucky to play for Gujarat. It's a beautiful ground. You get a lot of energy when you get so much support.

B0$ Definitely pretty special (playing at this venue), it's only about 40% full at the moment but it's already loud out here. It's going to be exciting when it gets fuller. (Playing for MI) It's a really good side to come into, lot of experience, I was here last year, it's a really good group and it's really exciting this year. We're doing a little bit better than we did at the start last year. Hopefully we can keep moving. (Favourite pitch) Delhi was pretty favourable for us bowlers, it was a bit inconsistent, that was pretty nice. It's been pretty hard for us (at Wankhede) fast bowlers this year, but that's what we're used to and that's what we're playing for.

B0$ "The highest number of sixes on an average has been hit at this venue along with Eden Gardens. This isn't the smallest of venues either. Square boundaries - 63 metres and 68 metres, straight down the ground it's 74 metres. It's unusually humid here. On the wicket, it's moist, not tacky in any way but certainly got some moisture in it. Don't be surprised if the fastmen do come into play in the powerplay. Even though it's red soil, I think it'll bounce traditionally but it'll just grip a little bit because of the extra moisture in it. The batters through the middle will be finding it very difficult this evening. Dew hasn't had a massive effect so far. It's overcast, chances are it (dew) might not have tonight either. Six out of six games - chasing teams have won."

commText: B0$, after losing their first two matches, won three on the bounce, but suffered a 13-run loss at the hands of Punjab Kings in a high-scoring encounter. Piyush Chawla has been their best bowler this season with the leggie picking 9 wickets at an impressive economy rate of 6.86. However, the other bowlers have been on the expensive side. It'll be interesting to see if they persist with Arjun Tendulkar who was taken to the cleaners by Sam Curran and Harpreet Singh. MI have a settled batting unit though. The openers are giving them good starts, Cam Green has struck a couple of fifties, SKY is coming back to form and young Tilak Varma is in great touch. Add Tim David's finishing skills to that and Mumbai have an enviable line-up.

B0$ come into this match on the back of a morale-boosting win. They snatched victory from the jaws of defeat against LSG where they defended a meagre total of 135. Barring that final over assault from Rinku Singh, the Titans have fared pretty well with the ball and Mohit Sharma has claimed two Player of the Match awards in three matches. The experienced duo of Mohammed Shami and Rashid have also been amongst the wickets. The defending champions have a brilliant record while chasing but they'll expect more 'intent' from their batters if they bat first. They have lost their two matches at home. Can Hardik and Co. put up a good show in front of their fans?

B0$ Five teams are currently on eight points. If the five-time IPL champions win today, they'll become the sixth side to join the group. If the defending champions prevail, they will join CSK at the top of the table. Who'll come out on top? It's Gujarat Titans (#4) vs Mumbai Indians (#7) at the Narendra Modi Stadium. Also, Hardik Pandya is up against his former franchise. Hello everyone and a warm welcome to the 35th game of the Indian Premier League.

"Rohit Sharma, any day, any time," says Harbhajan Singh on who he would rather bowl to - Rohit or MS Dhoni. "A very difficult batsman to bowl to, a class player in terms of batting skill... If Rohit bats from the beginning to the end, then there is no better player than him." 
 
Rohit has not exactly lived up to such words this IPL. Scores of 1, 21, 65, 20, 28 and 44 are not bad numbers, but that standard is for the lesser mortals. Greater things are expected from the India and the Mumbai Indians skipper. 
 
As they say, Rohit gets the starts, but conversions have eluded him and more often than not he is the first batsman to get out as an opener, leave aside batting till the end as Harbhajan hopes. A strike rate of over 142 is healthy but it's time he got into bigger scores for his franchise to have chances of progress in the league. 
 
At the Narendra Modi Stadium in Ahmedabad, where Mumbai Indians take on Gujarat Titans, on Tuesday evening, Rohit was seen having a long batting session on Monday evening. He was the lone MI batter at the centre wicket and the skipper must be aware that his contribution at the top of the order is in order. 
 
Six points from six games is not a bad start for a team that is notoriously slow off the blocks but with the league reaching the half-way stage, the four-time champions would be looking to their captain as well some of their bowlers, mainly Jofra Archer to step up. The team got out-batted by Punjab Kings at home in their last game but the subjugation started once they had conceded over 200 runs after choosing to bowl. 
 
But conceding 214 runs was no fault of Piyush Chawla, the season's best bowler for the franchise with nine wickets in six games and he will have extra advantage at the Motera which has been his home ground in domestic cricket. The veteran leggie said he is happy to come back to Gujarat for which he has been representing for six years in the domestic circuit. 
 
"I have been playing cricket for so long that wherever I go it feels like my home ground only," the leg-break bowler said on the eve of the match. "I have already played six years for Gujarat. It's a beautiful feeling to come back home but once you enter the field, you don't think about whether it is the home team or not. You want to put the best foot forward." 
 
Chawla will be the bowler that Gujarat Titans will be cautious of apart from Archer, who seems to have recovered from his elbow injury. The defending champions' season has seen two last over miracles - against Kolkata Knight Riders and Lucknow Super Giants. After being stunned by KKR's Rinku Singh, who hammered five sixes in the last over, the Titans did well to claims four wickets in the final over against LSG, courtesy Mohit Sharma. 
 
"The last win in Lucknow was a huge win for us. We have played very good cricket. We can improve certain areas. I don't think we need to be too concerned just yet. It is going to be a cracker of a game tomorrow," said David Miller of Titans, who admittedly, are in high spirits after the Lucknow jailbreak. 
 
With two teams that are in good form and packed with power players in all the areas, it is expected to be a cracker of a game, as Miller predicted, in front of 100,000 people at the Narendra Modi Stadium.
